  <!--   Chapter  3   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="3" style="c" sid="2TH 3" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="2TH 3:1" />In conclusion, pray for us, comrades<char style="sup">[a]</char>, so that the word of the Lord would
        spread rapidly<char style="sup">[b]</char> and would be glorified just as it did with you <verse eid="2TH 3:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="2TH 3:2" />and that we would be rescued from the perverse<char style="sup">[c]</char> and wicked people <char style="it">who
        resist us</char>: not everyone <char style="it">follows </char>the Faith, you see. <verse eid="2TH 3:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="2TH 3:3" />But the Lord is faithful, who will cause us to stand and will guard us from the Evil One. <verse eid="2TH 3:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="2TH 3:4" />I’ve reached the point where I’m convinced in <char style="it">the </char>Lord <char style="it">of good
        things </char>where you’re concerned, because you are doing and will do what we charged you with. <verse eid="2TH 3:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="2TH 3:5" />May the Lord direct your hearts to the love of God and to the steadfastness and endurance of Christ.<verse eid="2TH 3:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="2TH 3:6" />Now we charge you, comrades, in <char style="it">the</char> name of our Lord Jesus Christ (i.e., by the
        authority given to us by Jesus Christ) to stay away from all comrades who conduct themselves with a blatant
        disregard for the rules which have been set in place and not according to the bylaws, code of conduct,
        and best-practices established in perpetuity<char style="sup">[d]</char> which you received from us.<verse eid="2TH 3:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="2TH 3:7" />In this regard you know in yourselves from first-hand experience how necessary it is for you to follow
        our example, since we didn’t disregard the rules <char style="it">when we were</char> among you, <verse eid="2TH 3:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="2TH 3:8" />nor did we mooch any meals from anyone<char style="sup">[e]</char>—uh-uh—we were toiling day and night
        doing back-breaking labor so we wouldn’t be a burden on any of you— <verse eid="2TH 3:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="2TH 3:9" />Not that we don’t have the right <char style="it">to make you provide boarding for us</char>, but <char
        style="it">we choose to do what we did</char> instead so that we could offer ourselves to you as an example
        for you to imitate.<verse eid="2TH 3:9" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="2TH 3:10" />And in fact, when we were with you, we kept telling you to obey this rule: If a given person doesn’t
        want to work <char style="it">then </char>don’t let him have a meal at mealtime<char style="sup">[A]</char>.<verse eid="2TH 3:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="2TH 3:11" />In fact we hear that there are some people among you going about not following the rules, not doing any
        work but goofing off<char style="sup">[B]</char> instead. <verse eid="2TH 3:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="2TH 3:12" />To such people we charge and advise in <char style="it">the </char>Lord Jesus Christ <char style="it">certain
        admonishments </char>so that by keeping quiet while working they would eat their own meal (i.e., would
        be entitled to receive a meal).<verse eid="2TH 3:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="2TH 3:13" />But you, comrades—don’t get tired of doing good. <verse eid="2TH 3:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="2TH 3:14" />But if someone won’t obey the message <char style="it">we’re giving you </char>by <char style="it">this
        </char>letter <char style="it">were sending</char>, take note of this <char style="it">guy</char>: don’t
        associate with or get mixed up with him, so that he’ll be put to shame. <verse eid="2TH 3:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="2TH 3:15" />And don’t think of <char style="it">him </char>as an enemy, but warn and admonish <char style="it">him</char>
        as a comrade instead.<verse eid="2TH 3:15" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="2TH 3:16" />May the Lord of Peace himself grant you the peace throughout every <char style="it">circumstance </char>in
        every place<char style="sup">[f]</char>.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="2TH 3:16"><char style="it">May </char>the Lord <char style="it">be </char>with you all.<verse eid="2TH 3:16"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="2TH 3:17" />The greeting <char style="it">written here is in </char>Paul’s<char style="it"> handwriting</char>, which
        is a distinguishing feature of every letter <char style="it">I write</char>:</para>
    <para style="p" vid="2TH 3:17"><char style="sc">THIS IS THE WAY I WRITE</char><char style="sup">[C]</char>.<verse eid="2TH 3:17"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
